[Amit Varma]: subject of this episode, you're doing this awesome political podcast with the Hindustan

00:03:27.640 --> 00:03:32.400
[Amit Varma]: Times. So why don't you tell us a little bit about these elections? What's what's happening?

00:03:32.400 --> 00:03:37.200
[Guest]: Who's gonna win? Small question. So I think things look very different today than they

00:03:37.200 --> 00:03:43.360
[Amit Varma]: did even at the start of 2019. And we are recording this, by the way, on March 18. This

00:03:43.360 --> 00:03:47.000
[Amit Varma]: episode is going to be released on April 1. So a lot could have changed. Kindly don't

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:48.960
[Guest]: hold Milan responsible for anything.

00:03:48.960 --> 00:03:52.520
[Guest]: That's right. Hopefully everyone will forget by the time May 23 comes around and we've

00:03:52.520 --> 00:04:00.640
[Guest]: counted votes. I think that the momentum is shifted quite significantly towards Modi and

00:04:00.640 --> 00:04:06.800
[Guest]: the BJP. And it's not only because of the events at Pulwama and the aftermath, although

00:04:06.800 --> 00:04:12.040
[Guest]: I do think that that was a net positive for him. But I think as we've moved towards the

00:04:12.040 --> 00:04:20.960
[Guest]: main campaign, Modi's attributes, his claim to fame, decisiveness, leadership, nationalism

00:04:20.960 --> 00:04:26.960
[Guest]: have come to the fore. And here I think we see the opposition's weaknesses in terms of

00:04:26.960 --> 00:04:35.280
[Guest]: both coming up and answering the leadership question, but also, you know, trying to articulate

00:04:35.280 --> 00:04:42.400
[Guest]: a cogent counter narrative to what Modi and the BJP have to offer. And I think for many

00:04:42.400 --> 00:04:49.320
[Guest]: Indians when they look at the opposition, a lot of their charges seem rather petty.

00:04:49.320 --> 00:04:53.720
[Guest]: Because I think in the most parts of this country, certainly in North India, maybe less

00:04:53.720 --> 00:05:00.720
[Guest]: so in South India, Modi is popular. You know, people like him. People would like to believe

00:05:00.720 --> 00:05:04.440
[Guest]: that he has their best interests at heart, that he has clean intent. So they're willing

00:05:04.440 --> 00:05:12.800
[Guest]: to forgive quite a lot of policy missteps, whether it's, you know, GST, demonetization,

00:05:12.800 --> 00:05:18.880
[Guest]: you know, various other grievances with respect to the economy, and instead focus on the positive.

00:05:18.880 --> 00:05:24.840
[Guest]: So I think what the recent Balakot strike does is to give people who are hunting for

00:05:24.840 --> 00:05:29.880
[Guest]: an excuse to support Modi, give them a reason to vote for him on election day.

00:05:29.880 --> 00:05:34.440
[Amit Varma]: Now, you know, I am a Namche commentator based in a city. So whenever someone asks me, what

00:05:34.440 --> 00:05:37.640
[Amit Varma]: do you think is going to happen in the election, my honest answer has to be listen, I don't

00:05:37.640 --> 00:05:43.160
[Amit Varma]: have a clue, because it's just so many, it's a conglomeration of local elections, you know,

00:05:43.160 --> 00:05:46.920
[Amit Varma]: there are so many factors in play. And it's incredibly hard for someone like me to have

00:05:46.920 --> 00:05:51.000
[Amit Varma]: a sense and to leave my biases aside. But as a political scientist, you're obviously

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:55.160
[Amit Varma]: looking beyond all of that. And you're trying, you know, you have, what's the kind of data

00:05:55.160 --> 00:05:59.560
[Amit Varma]: you look at? What are the kind of trends that you look at to try to get a sense of what

00:05:59.560 --> 00:06:01.640
[Guest]: is really happening in the country?

00:06:01.640 --> 00:06:09.360
[Guest]: So, you know, obviously, there are huge questions around the validity and accuracy of survey

00:06:09.360 --> 00:06:15.520
[Guest]: data. Because we have too many instances in the past where surveys have sort of gotten

00:06:15.520 --> 00:06:20.040
[Guest]: things wrong, both in terms of vote share and in terms of seat share. But I think the

00:06:20.040 --> 00:06:25.820
[Guest]: way in which one can look at survey data is to sort of look at trends, because they do

00:06:25.820 --> 00:06:32.560
[Guest]: tend to be kind of correlated with one another. So you could see very clearly, from, say,

00:06:32.560 --> 00:06:38.320
[Guest]: the height of the BJP's power post-Luther British, to where we are today, definitely

00:06:38.320 --> 00:06:44.560
[Guest]: a sort of narrowing of the race. And then more recently, again, a widening, and I think

00:06:44.560 --> 00:06:49.480
[Guest]: I expect that widening will either grow or kind of stay the same, barring, you know,

00:06:49.480 --> 00:06:53.280
[Guest]: major unforeseen events in the next couple of weeks. So I think that's one. I mean, I

00:06:53.280 --> 00:06:59.280
[Guest]: think the second is trying to go beyond the sort of horse race of, you know, this leader

00:06:59.280 --> 00:07:03.860
[Guest]: said X and the other leader said Y. But look at some of the underlying trends, whether

00:07:03.860 --> 00:07:09.660
[Guest]: it's with young voters or female voters, their participation, what they're saying matters

00:07:09.660 --> 00:07:10.660
[Guest]: to them.

00:07:10.660 --> 00:07:16.760
[Guest]: You know, for instance, one of the striking things about 2014 that we were able to detect

00:07:16.760 --> 00:07:21.000
[Guest]: pre-election, not that we had foreseen a single party majority of the size, I don't want to

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:28.320
[Guest]: claim credit for that because I didn't, but that there was a surprising convergence in

00:07:28.320 --> 00:07:33.100
[Guest]: priorities among rural and urban dwellers. They both were saying the exact same things

00:07:33.100 --> 00:07:39.160
[Guest]: mattered to them. The top three issues in both types of places were price rise, lack

00:07:39.160 --> 00:07:45.640
[Guest]: of sort of development jobs, and corruption. Now, the precise ordering of those three questions

00:07:45.640 --> 00:07:51.440
[Guest]: might vary from Telenado to, you know, Bihar, but they were always the top three issues,

00:07:51.440 --> 00:07:52.840
[Amit Varma]: both in urban and in rural.

00:07:52.840 --> 00:07:57.000
[Amit Varma]: And there are people who sort of say that, you know, for example, just to pick one of

00:07:57.000 --> 00:08:02.120
[Amit Varma]: those issues, which is development, that people who cited development to vote for the BJP

00:08:02.120 --> 00:08:07.920
[Amit Varma]: were actually rationalizing or putting a respectable face to their innate bigotry or whatever the

00:08:07.920 --> 00:08:11.320
[Amit Varma]: case might be. And they were really voting for other reasons. I mean, so how does one

00:08:11.320 --> 00:08:16.320
[Amit Varma]: really know why are people really voting? What are the forces at play here? Because

00:08:16.320 --> 00:08:21.560
[Amit Varma]: there are a lot of complex forces at play here, which will not show up on this kind

00:08:21.560 --> 00:08:25.560
[Amit Varma]: of survey data, right? Because you will never see these sort of trends.

00:08:25.560 --> 00:08:30.720
[Guest]: Right. No, I mean, I think, you know, one of the major problems in survey research is

00:08:30.720 --> 00:08:36.080
[Guest]: what social scientists call social desirability bias, right? Basically, a numerator knocks

00:08:36.080 --> 00:08:40.080
[Guest]: on my door and asks me a bunch of questions, and I don't want him or her to judge me in

00:08:40.080 --> 00:08:44.080
[Guest]: the wrong way. And so therefore, I sort of tell them, you know, what I think they want

00:08:44.080 --> 00:08:48.000
[Guest]: to hear. So I think that obviously is an issue. There's ways of getting around that through

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:52.720
[Guest]: experimentation. You know, there's survey experiments where you sort of give people

00:08:52.720 --> 00:08:59.040
[Guest]: vignettes or different kinds of prompts and see kind of what changes their thing. So some

00:08:59.040 --> 00:09:04.640
[Guest]: people have tried that. I think the other thing, though, just on the economy, you know,

00:09:04.640 --> 00:09:09.800
[Guest]: I'm one of these people who believes that there has been a shift in the Indian electorate

00:09:09.800 --> 00:09:14.760
[Guest]: that traditionally there's been this truism that good economics doesn't make for good

00:09:14.760 --> 00:09:21.600
[Guest]: politics. That if you look over the vast stretch of post-independence history, particularly

00:09:21.600 --> 00:09:27.040
[Guest]: when we have data, say, the last three, four decades, that there's no apparent correlation

00:09:27.040 --> 00:09:33.760
[Guest]: between a government's economic performance and how that incumbent does at the time of

00:09:33.760 --> 00:09:38.280
[Guest]: election. But what's interesting is if you start disaggregating that relationship by

00:09:38.280 --> 00:09:44.440
[Guest]: decade, you see actually starting around the year 2000, there is much more of a close correlation.

00:09:44.440 --> 00:09:50.800
[Guest]: In other words, there are positive electoral rewards to better growth. Now, is this of

00:09:50.800 --> 00:09:55.480
[Guest]: extremely robust and strong relationship? No. Can it explain all the variation? Not

00:09:55.480 --> 00:09:59.680
[Guest]: at all. But I do think that there has been a subtle shift. You know, part of that is

00:09:59.680 --> 00:10:06.440
[Guest]: once people taste the fruits of rapid growth or high growth, they start to demand more.

00:10:06.440 --> 00:10:10.440
[Guest]: So you know, one of the puzzling things about this election, if Modi and the BJP come back

00:10:10.440 --> 00:10:16.280
[Guest]: to power, is clearly growth has been very uneven. And so what were the other factors

00:10:16.280 --> 00:10:20.680
[Guest]: that were shaping the electorate in this race beyond just sort of bread and butter issues

00:10:20.680 --> 00:10:22.920
[Guest]: like growth, jobs, inflation, and so on?

00:10:22.920 --> 00:10:26.160
[Amit Varma]: Siddharth Tavakoli And I think the other, just to sort of add

00:10:26.160 --> 00:10:30.800
[Amit Varma]: to that, even if there are more people in the electorate who are claiming a concern

00:10:30.800 --> 00:10:36.760
[Amit Varma]: for economic issues, that doesn't necessarily mean that they'll promote the right kind of

00:10:36.760 --> 00:10:39.760
[Amit Varma]: policies. For example, if you ask a farmer today, what do you want most? Do you want

00:10:39.760 --> 00:10:43.600
[Amit Varma]: a Hindu Rashtra? He'll probably say, no, no, man, I just, you know, do something about

00:10:43.600 --> 00:10:47.120
[Amit Varma]: the economics. I want development. But what he has in mind is farm loan waivers, which

00:10:47.120 --> 00:10:53.360
[Amit Varma]: are just a short term fix, and not any of the structural reforms that we actually need.

00:10:53.360 --> 00:10:59.720
[Guest]: So you know, I think, I mean, this is very relevant to the current Prime Minister, because

00:10:59.720 --> 00:11:06.020
[Guest]: in 2014, you know, Modi became something of a Rorschach test. We all sort of projected

00:11:06.020 --> 00:11:12.880
[Guest]: onto him what we wanted to see, right? So some people saw the Hindu strongman of 2002.

00:11:12.880 --> 00:11:20.160
[Guest]: Other people saw kind of a more market friendly, libertarian minded, you know, kind of modernizer.

00:11:20.160 --> 00:11:24.920
[Guest]: And in reality, we've sort of got, I think, something that's closer to the middle. But

00:11:24.920 --> 00:11:30.640
[Guest]: you know, he was very careful in the run up to the 2014 polls, of not really saying all

00:11:30.640 --> 00:11:37.240
[Guest]: that much, in terms of specific policy, right? It was subcassades, because it was good governance,

00:11:37.240 --> 00:11:44.120
[Guest]: it was rejuvenating the Indian economy, right, making India kind of a world leader on the

00:11:44.120 --> 00:11:47.920
[Guest]: global stage, once again, I mean, these were sort of platitudes. And then I think we all

00:11:47.920 --> 00:11:52.920
[Guest]: filled in the blanks with the kind of policy menus that we hoped he would sort of pick

00:11:52.920 --> 00:11:53.920
[Amit Varma]: up.

00:11:53.920 --> 00:11:58.680
[Amit Varma]: And now that we know that, and would you therefore say that if your contention is that people

00:11:58.680 --> 00:12:03.080
[Amit Varma]: do care about economics, would you then say that maybe the Congress missed the trick a

00:12:03.080 --> 00:12:07.680
[Amit Varma]: little bit here by focusing on Rafale, by focusing on Pulwama, and so on, when they

00:12:07.680 --> 00:12:12.360
[Amit Varma]: should perhaps just have been talking jobs, jobs, jobs, where are the jobs?

00:12:12.360 --> 00:12:18.800
[Guest]: One of the most enduring mysteries about this campaign cycle is why the Congress has not

00:12:18.800 --> 00:12:24.160
[Guest]: just done that. In my personal view, I think they've wasted a lot of time with the Rafale

00:12:24.160 --> 00:12:30.560
[Guest]: scandal, because I think frankly, outside of a small coterie of people in urban metros,

00:12:30.560 --> 00:12:35.440
[Guest]: not that many people are either going to care, or are going to be able to understand what

00:12:35.440 --> 00:12:39.940
[Guest]: the deal is about. You know, we were talking about this before, if you asked a veteran

00:12:39.940 --> 00:12:46.160
[Guest]: defense expert to give you a 15 second soundbite on Rafale, I think he or she would really

00:12:46.160 --> 00:12:52.240
[Guest]: struggle. And so I fear that for the Congress, they're also falling into the same trap now

00:12:52.240 --> 00:12:57.460
[Guest]: with this Pulwama thing, talking about China, how is this government not able to get China

00:12:57.460 --> 00:13:03.480
[Guest]: to vote in the UN Security Council to sanction Masoud Azhar, the head of Jaish-e-Mohammed,

00:13:03.480 --> 00:13:11.760
[Guest]: criticizing Ajit Doval for his hand in getting Masoud Azhar back as part of the hostage exchange.

00:13:11.760 --> 00:13:16.760
[Guest]: These are losers in terms of issues for the Congress, I think that they should instead

00:13:16.760 --> 00:13:23.840
[Guest]: focus and Priyanka Gandhi did this in Ahmedabad the other day, talking about jobs, agrarian

00:13:23.840 --> 00:13:28.240
[Guest]: distress and so on and so forth. But it may be too little too late. And I think the other

00:13:28.240 --> 00:13:33.760
[Guest]: thing that is hurting the Congress is, they don't seem to be able to articulate a kind

00:13:33.760 --> 00:13:40.440
[Guest]: of alternative future. So what is it that they would do if they came to power? So we

00:13:40.440 --> 00:13:47.280
[Guest]: see some strands of ideas, you know, more loan waivers, a better income support scheme.

00:13:47.280 --> 00:13:53.720
[Guest]: But I think a lot of folks have sort of lost confidence that on the ideas front anyway,

00:13:53.720 --> 00:13:57.600
[Guest]: they have a clear sense of, you know, what they would do if they came to power.

00:13:57.600 --> 00:14:00.080
[Amit Varma]: Dr. Ahmed Sabir Let's kind of move on from talking about

00:14:00.080 --> 00:14:06.040
[Amit Varma]: these elections to a subject that actually, you know, affects all the parties where all

00:14:06.040 --> 00:14:10.120
[Amit Varma]: the parties are really equally guilty, which is crime and politics, you know, as your book

00:14:10.120 --> 00:14:14.680
[Amit Varma]: describes in such detail, you know, criminality in politics is not restricted to this party

00:14:14.680 --> 00:14:20.880
[Amit Varma]: or that party, despite all the noises that Modi made in 2014. The BJP is as guilty of

00:14:20.880 --> 00:14:25.560
[Amit Varma]: it as anyone. And interestingly, people seem to think it's a problem in the Hindi heartland.

00:14:25.560 --> 00:14:30.200
[Amit Varma]: But as your book shows, it's spread out all across the country. And it's got deep structural

00:14:30.200 --> 00:14:37.920
[Amit Varma]: reasons. And I found all of that very fascinating. And I was quite taken with your approach to

00:14:37.920 --> 00:14:44.160
[Amit Varma]: handling this issue, which was to think of Indian politics in terms of markets to talk

00:14:44.160 --> 00:14:49.800
[Amit Varma]: about the political marketplace and examine the incentives within that marketplace. And

00:14:49.800 --> 00:14:54.880
[Amit Varma]: then from there, figure out why we are where we are. So how did you sort of, you know,

00:14:54.880 --> 00:14:57.520
[Amit Varma]: arrive at that approach, that way of looking at this problem?

00:14:57.520 --> 00:15:02.600
[Guest]: Dr. Ahmed Sabir So, you know, I went in, very influenced by

00:15:02.600 --> 00:15:07.440
[Guest]: what the global literature says. And if I had to summarize the prevailing wisdom in

00:15:07.440 --> 00:15:14.280
[Guest]: the political economy literature, it's basically about information, that where voters lack

00:15:14.280 --> 00:15:19.560
[Guest]: adequate information about the candidates they're voting for, they are liable to choose

00:15:19.560 --> 00:15:25.080
[Guest]: quote unquote, bad candidates, bad meaning corrupt, dishonest, tainted, criminal in some

00:15:25.080 --> 00:15:31.480
[Guest]: way. And so if you just give them that information, they're able to update their calculation and

00:15:31.480 --> 00:15:36.160
[Guest]: choose quote unquote, good politicians who are the kind of honest or non criminals. And

00:15:36.160 --> 00:15:43.720
[Guest]: so I had begun to spend some time with voters and political campaigns in India. And what

00:15:43.720 --> 00:15:50.600
[Guest]: I quickly realized is that wasn't the story. Many people were voting for these criminals,

00:15:50.600 --> 00:15:54.600
[Guest]: and they had this information. But there was another reason they were doing so. And so

00:15:54.600 --> 00:15:59.420
[Guest]: then I started to think about this question of the demand, where does the demand for this

00:15:59.420 --> 00:16:03.980
[Guest]: kind of a figure, whether it's a Papu Yadav or an Anand Singh or some of the people I

00:16:03.980 --> 00:16:09.840
[Guest]: talk about in my book? And where do these people come from? Right? I mean, at the end

00:16:09.840 --> 00:16:15.100
[Guest]: of the day, it's parties who are giving them tickets. It's not you know, if you're an independent

00:16:15.100 --> 00:16:19.840
[Guest]: in this country, it's very, very hard to win elections. I mean, the independents historically

00:16:19.840 --> 00:16:25.280
[Guest]: have performed very, very poorly. And so that's really how I backed into this demand supply

00:16:25.280 --> 00:16:30.200
[Guest]: framework. And then I sort of thought, you know, let's try to it's almost like an onion

00:16:30.200 --> 00:16:34.920
[Guest]: that you're peeling the layers successively, you know, to try to get at the core of the

00:16:34.920 --> 00:16:40.180
[Guest]: story. But you know, I came in at thinking I knew what the answer was only to be very

00:16:40.180 --> 00:16:46.920
[Guest]: quickly proven wrong. And that put me at odds with what other people, you know, in the academy

00:16:46.920 --> 00:16:54.520
[Guest]: were sort of saying, but I thought it was rather unfair to transpose, you know, all

00:16:54.520 --> 00:16:57.920
[Guest]: the work that had been done in other countries and just say, well, you know, India probably

00:16:57.920 --> 00:16:58.920
[Guest]: is the same.

00:16:58.920 --> 00:17:03.400
[Amit Varma]: No, and it's it's struck me while reading it that it's a very fine work of public choice

00:17:03.400 --> 00:17:08.280
[Amit Varma]: economics and you're a trained political scientist. So let's take a detour for a moment because

00:17:08.280 --> 00:17:12.080
[Amit Varma]: I meant to ask you about this. Tell me a little bit about, you know, how you became a political

00:17:12.080 --> 00:17:16.240
[Amit Varma]: scientist and what are the kind of things you studied for this?

00:17:16.240 --> 00:17:23.760
[Guest]: Sure. So I studied politics and economics as an undergraduate in the US. And I didn't

00:17:23.760 --> 00:17:27.440
[Guest]: really know that you could make a career out of that. I just thought, you know, I'm interested,

00:17:27.440 --> 00:17:34.040
[Guest]: this is sort of a hobby. And I ended up spending a summer interning at the Pentagon. And so

00:17:34.040 --> 00:17:37.740
[Guest]: my eyes were open to the different kinds of careers one could have. And then I stayed

00:17:37.740 --> 00:17:43.440
[Guest]: on for an additional semester and worked at a think tank. And so when I graduated, I was

00:17:43.440 --> 00:17:47.520
[Guest]: sort of bitten by the bug. I knew I wanted to come back. So I sort of, you know, worked

00:17:47.520 --> 00:17:52.940
[Guest]: the trenches as very lowly research assistant at a series of think tanks. But no think tanks

00:17:52.940 --> 00:17:56.760
[Guest]: and research institutes are a funny place. So there's a real caste system. You know,

00:17:56.760 --> 00:18:01.460
[Guest]: you're either the lowly researcher assistant, or you're a fellow or a senior fellow carrying

00:18:01.460 --> 00:18:02.460
[Guest]: out your research.

00:18:02.460 --> 00:18:03.460
[Amit Varma]: There's no middle class.

00:18:03.460 --> 00:18:08.360
[Guest]: There's no middle class and there's no social mobility. So I decided, you know, by default,

00:18:08.360 --> 00:18:13.440
[Guest]: I basically if I wanted to kind of jump ranks, I was going to have to go do a PhD. And so

00:18:13.440 --> 00:18:18.680
[Guest]: I decided to do a PhD in political science. But funnily enough, up until this point in

00:18:18.680 --> 00:18:26.120
[Guest]: time, I had never worked on India. As an Indian American, as the son of Indian immigrants,

00:18:26.120 --> 00:18:31.760
[Guest]: my natural reaction was to do the exact opposite of whatever my culture or family was. And

00:18:31.760 --> 00:18:36.000
[Guest]: so for years and years and years, I thought who would want to do India? It's not exotic

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:40.480
[Guest]: enough. You know, I know it already. Of course, none of those things were true. And I think

00:18:40.480 --> 00:18:46.240
[Guest]: it wasn't until I got to graduate school, when I started to realize that, A, there's

00:18:46.240 --> 00:18:52.240
[Guest]: so much we don't know about India. B, that's a place where you can really make a contribution.

00:18:52.240 --> 00:18:56.800
[Guest]: And C, you know, PhDs are six or seven years long in the States if you're doing political

00:18:56.800 --> 00:19:00.600
[Guest]: science. So this has to be something that is going to be both personally and professionally

00:19:00.600 --> 00:19:05.120
[Guest]: rewarding to you. And the light bulb just sort of went off and India kind of floated

00:19:05.120 --> 00:19:11.440
[Guest]: to the top. And so I spent a summer here in New Delhi working at CSDS, you know, who are

00:19:11.440 --> 00:19:16.920
[Guest]: the ones who do regular polling. And I'd never look back.

00:19:16.920 --> 00:19:22.960
[Amit Varma]: Right. And getting back to the book, When Crime Pays, so you essentially ask five questions

00:19:22.960 --> 00:19:27.440
[Amit Varma]: in the book to try and figure out why our politics is so infested with crime. And, and

00:19:27.440 --> 00:19:30.400
[Amit Varma]: of course, the first three have to deal with incentives, which is, you know, the first

00:19:30.400 --> 00:19:36.560
[Amit Varma]: one is, why do criminals gravitate towards politics in the first place? The second is,

00:19:36.560 --> 00:19:43.840
[Amit Varma]: why do parties choose to have criminal candidates? And the third is, why do voters vote for criminal

00:19:43.840 --> 00:19:47.480
[Amit Varma]: candidates, even when they know that they're criminals? In fact, like you point out that

00:19:47.480 --> 00:19:52.400
[Amit Varma]: it's often a feature, not a bug, that they're voting for these guys because of their criminal

00:19:52.400 --> 00:19:56.840
[Amit Varma]: backgrounds and not in spite of it. So let's kind of get to the first of those questions,

00:19:56.840 --> 00:20:01.440
[Amit Varma]: which is, what are the incentives for criminals to get into politics? And you know, as you

00:20:01.440 --> 00:20:06.800
[Amit Varma]: kind of pointed out in your book that it wasn't always like this, that perhaps up to the 70s,

00:20:06.800 --> 00:20:10.080
[Amit Varma]: criminals played a kind of a side role where they would help politicians, they would do

00:20:10.080 --> 00:20:16.160
[Amit Varma]: booth capturing or mobilize voters and stuff like that. But at some point, something fundamentally

00:20:16.160 --> 00:20:21.040
[Amit Varma]: shifts in the political landscape that prompts them to make the move themselves. Tell me

00:20:21.040 --> 00:20:22.040
[Guest]: about this.

00:20:22.040 --> 00:20:27.680
[Guest]: That's right. So if you go back and read the earliest reports of elections in 1952, in

00:20:27.680 --> 00:20:34.320
[Guest]: the early 50s, you see in the Election Commission's official reports, you know, scattered mentions

00:20:34.320 --> 00:20:41.840
[Guest]: of the use of kind of gundas on the part of politicians and political parties to suppress

00:20:41.840 --> 00:20:46.720
[Guest]: voters, if you think they're going to vote against you to mobilize voters to capture

00:20:46.720 --> 00:20:53.240
[Guest]: boots to kind of do the dirty work of politicians. And that starts to increase, it's pioneered

00:20:53.240 --> 00:20:57.820
[Guest]: by the Congress, and then people start to sort of copycat what the Congress is doing.

00:20:57.820 --> 00:21:01.960
[Guest]: But they're very much at the periphery of politics. They are not the candidates, they

00:21:01.960 --> 00:21:06.440
[Guest]: are sort of the hired guns. And the quid pro quo there is, look, if we come to power, we'll

00:21:06.440 --> 00:21:11.280
[Guest]: protect you. But you've got to do this, you know, for us. So the incentives were totally

00:21:11.280 --> 00:21:18.040
[Guest]: compatible. Several things started to change slowly over time at first. One is that you

00:21:18.040 --> 00:21:23.480
[Guest]: start to see the rise of identity politics. And so some of these cast expressions get

00:21:23.480 --> 00:21:29.400
[Guest]: mobilized and activated. And these gundas are forms of that expression. By and large,

00:21:29.400 --> 00:21:35.080
[Guest]: a lot of the politicians were still from the Hindu upper castes. Number two is you start

00:21:35.080 --> 00:21:41.360
[Guest]: to see a hollowing out of the state apparatus, particularly the law and order institutions.

00:21:41.360 --> 00:21:46.540
[Guest]: And money becomes more important as the population is growing and candidates are trying to sort

00:21:46.540 --> 00:21:53.320
[Guest]: of woo voters. But where you really see this kind of critical break is around the Indira's

00:21:53.320 --> 00:22:00.280
[Guest]: time in the 1970s, where at that point, two things happen. One is that the Congress system

00:22:00.280 --> 00:22:05.480
[Guest]: starts to collapse under the weight of its own contradictions, which then opens up political

00:22:05.480 --> 00:22:09.200
[Guest]: space for these political entrepreneurs to rush in and grab a piece of that.

00:22:09.200 --> 00:22:11.200
[Guest]: Sadanand Rajan What's the Congress system?

00:22:11.200 --> 00:22:14.480
[Guest]: Matthew 15 So the Congress system essentially was, you

00:22:14.480 --> 00:22:22.480
[Guest]: know, this very cultivated sense of a system of sort of patronage and clientelism overseen

00:22:22.480 --> 00:22:29.480
[Guest]: by the Congress, which, you know, meant that the Congress had reasonably good local party

00:22:29.480 --> 00:22:35.600
[Guest]: organizations and political networks. Over time, as Indira begins to centralize more

00:22:35.600 --> 00:22:43.020
[Guest]: power in her own hands, some of these networks start to atrophy. Now, there's an underlying

00:22:43.020 --> 00:22:49.760
[Guest]: weakness already generating because again, as I said, the Congress claimed to represent

00:22:49.760 --> 00:22:53.640
[Guest]: everybody. But in fact, if you look at who the politicians were, who actually were on

00:22:53.640 --> 00:22:58.040
[Guest]: the ballots got elected, it tended to be from a relatively thin band of society. So there's

00:22:58.040 --> 00:23:04.400
[Guest]: already some sort of disenchantment. And a lot of these criminal entrepreneurs realized

00:23:04.400 --> 00:23:10.160
[Guest]: that over the years, they had accumulated resources, they could accumulate black money,

00:23:10.160 --> 00:23:16.000
[Guest]: and they knew how to move it around, that they became the mediators between the state

00:23:16.000 --> 00:23:19.800
[Guest]: and society. But yet they weren't getting any of the credit, they weren't getting the

00:23:19.800 --> 00:23:24.520
[Guest]: financial rents necessarily, because the politicians were taking their cut. They weren't getting

00:23:24.520 --> 00:23:28.600
[Guest]: the ego rents or the psychological rents, because at the end of the day, they were just,

00:23:28.600 --> 00:23:33.320
[Guest]: you know, the kind of hired gun. And so they decided in the book, I use the kind of analogy

00:23:33.320 --> 00:23:38.320
[Guest]: of, you know, vertical integration, right? So when a manufacturer decides that, you know,

00:23:38.320 --> 00:23:43.660
[Guest]: I'm building cars, I should take advantage of economies of scale and start to manufacture

00:23:43.660 --> 00:23:48.560
[Guest]: my own tires, criminals essentially started to do that. So you start to see particularly

00:23:48.560 --> 00:23:54.720
[Guest]: in the 1970s, in the post emergency time, criminals themselves directly standing for

00:23:54.720 --> 00:24:00.680
[Guest]: election, you know, and they say things like, look, everyone was coming, paying their respects

00:24:00.680 --> 00:24:06.480
[Guest]: to the politician, and we were getting nothing, but they rely on us. So why don't we just

00:24:06.480 --> 00:24:11.320
[Guest]: cut out the middleman and just and just sort of do it ourselves. And so that system starts

00:24:11.320 --> 00:24:17.000
[Guest]: to rapidly escalate. And one of the things that Indira Gandhi did, which now when we

00:24:17.000 --> 00:24:25.880
[Guest]: look back, was extremely harmful to India's political economy, is she she banned corporate

00:24:25.880 --> 00:24:30.240
[Guest]: donations to political parties. Now, that sounds to some people may be like a good thing.

00:24:30.240 --> 00:24:35.360
[Guest]: But essentially, what it did is then shifted all political funding underground, and she

00:24:35.360 --> 00:24:40.800
[Guest]: never replaced it with something else. In Europe, they've replaced it with the public

00:24:40.800 --> 00:24:46.560
[Guest]: financing system. And so then there really was a premium on how do you aggregate and

00:24:46.560 --> 00:24:50.440
[Guest]: move this black money and criminals had an advantage there. And so we're still living

00:24:50.440 --> 00:24:55.800
[Guest]: with the legacy of that policy decision. As you know, you know, most money which gets

00:24:55.800 --> 00:25:00.640
[Guest]: spent in election time is unaccounted for, right? So we have official estimates. But

00:25:00.640 --> 00:25:05.280
[Guest]: we know that the actual numbers are probably 10x, you know, what politicians themselves

00:25:05.280 --> 00:25:06.280
[Guest]: report if not more.

00:25:06.280 --> 00:25:11.160
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, another factor you mentioned while analyzing the incentives of the criminals

00:25:11.160 --> 00:25:15.840
[Amit Varma]: themselves is the rise of anti incumbency, that it was far more common in the 50s or

00:25:15.840 --> 00:25:22.440
[Amit Varma]: 60s to retain your seat. But as anti incumbency went up through the late 60s, 70s, 80s, what

00:25:22.440 --> 00:25:26.440
[Amit Varma]: inevitably happened was that if you were a criminal don, like you talk about how the

00:25:26.440 --> 00:25:30.760
[Amit Varma]: goondas became dada, so let's say you're a dada of your neighborhood, rather than help

00:25:30.760 --> 00:25:34.800
[Amit Varma]: one politician and then in the next election, he goes out of power and you're on the outside

00:25:34.800 --> 00:25:39.320
[Amit Varma]: again, why not just make sure you are part of the system and you stand instead and you

00:25:39.320 --> 00:25:41.800
[Amit Varma]: make as much money as you can and all of that.

00:25:41.800 --> 00:25:46.680
[Guest]: Yeah, that's really a central characteristic. You know, when the Congress was so dominant,

00:25:46.680 --> 00:25:51.400
[Guest]: if you were the goonda, the night before the election day, you could sort of sleep easy,

00:25:51.400 --> 00:25:55.840
[Guest]: you could rest easy, because odds are that your Congress politician you work with is

00:25:55.840 --> 00:26:01.880
[Guest]: going to come back to power. Once that uncertainty increases, you're in a dangerous situation,

00:26:01.880 --> 00:26:08.600
[Guest]: because if that patron of yours loses, then both the state and the opposition, which knows

00:26:08.600 --> 00:26:13.160
[Guest]: about your dealings with the Congress could come after you. So they essentially decided,

00:26:13.160 --> 00:26:18.760
[Guest]: why don't we just take our own fate, you know, into our own hands. And that's what they decided

00:26:18.760 --> 00:26:26.000
[Guest]: to do. And of course, very soon, they realized that, you know, this wasn't just politically

00:26:26.000 --> 00:26:28.120
[Guest]: profitable, it was also economically profitable.

00:26:28.120 --> 00:26:32.800
[Amit Varma]: And you've got a great chapter which talks about how exactly how economically profitable

00:26:32.800 --> 00:26:37.880
[Amit Varma]: it is, which is, you know, where you, you coined the term rents Raj, is that your term?

00:26:37.880 --> 00:26:44.680
[Guest]: That's not my term. I think the rents Raj came first. Well, there was the resource Raj,

00:26:44.680 --> 00:26:49.880
[Guest]: which is actually a term that Raghuram Rajan came up with. And the rents Raj was something

00:26:49.880 --> 00:26:55.120
[Guest]: that the former chief economic advisor, Irvin Subramaniam, sort of adapted, you know, from

00:26:55.120 --> 00:26:56.120
[Guest]: what Rajan said.

00:26:56.120 --> 00:27:00.680
[Amit Varma]: So tell me sort of about the different kinds of rents. So can you can you first define

00:27:00.680 --> 00:27:02.680
[Amit Varma]: rent seeking for me for those of my listeners?

00:27:02.680 --> 00:27:07.800
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, I think it's basically, you know, how do you make money without having

00:27:07.800 --> 00:27:12.120
[Guest]: to do very much? And by the way, productive activity, right? I mean, so people who they

00:27:12.120 --> 00:27:16.560
[Guest]: want a free lunch, I think that's one way of thinking about it. And so, you know, what

00:27:16.560 --> 00:27:24.120
[Guest]: I talk about in the book is that, you know, you have these quite powerful changes in Indian

00:27:24.120 --> 00:27:30.920
[Guest]: political economy. So you have the changing social makeup of our political class, the

00:27:30.920 --> 00:27:37.120
[Guest]: enfranchised men of Dalits and backwards, and so on. You have economic changes from

00:27:37.120 --> 00:27:42.380
[Guest]: a more command and control economy to a more market driven economy. Politically, of course,

00:27:42.380 --> 00:27:46.800
[Guest]: you move from a one party dominant system to a more fragmented multi party system. But

00:27:46.800 --> 00:27:53.300
[Guest]: the one thing which really is constant throughout, you know, post independence India is the strength

00:27:53.300 --> 00:27:59.520
[Guest]: of institutions is always lagging behind those other changes that there really haven't been

00:27:59.520 --> 00:28:05.920
[Guest]: too many governments who have prioritized administrative and governance reform. And so in that delta

00:28:05.920 --> 00:28:11.880
[Guest]: between all of these pressures and aspirations comes in the opportunity to sort of, you know,

00:28:11.880 --> 00:28:19.760
[Guest]: make rents, right. And so when you have market opening in 1991, a lot of the ability to make

00:28:19.760 --> 00:28:26.160
[Guest]: money gets monopolized by people who are able to manipulate, you know, the leftovers of

00:28:26.160 --> 00:28:31.160
[Guest]: the regulatory sort of regime. So in some cases, you have regulatory capture. In some

00:28:31.160 --> 00:28:36.760
[Guest]: cases, you open up or you privatize, but you then don't re regulate, which is often something

00:28:36.760 --> 00:28:42.840
[Guest]: that you have to do to make sure that there's not monopoly control. And so there's huge

00:28:42.840 --> 00:28:48.680
[Guest]: rents from regulation. There's huge rents also from extraction, right? So the whole

00:28:48.680 --> 00:28:54.480
[Guest]: topic of natural resources wasn't really something that was on the agenda in 1991. And we saw

00:28:54.480 --> 00:28:59.840
[Guest]: the fallout from that in the UPA to government, right? I mean, all of the major scandals involved,

00:28:59.840 --> 00:29:06.000
[Guest]: whether it was land, coal mining, telecommunication spectrum, which is a kind of natural resource.

00:29:06.000 --> 00:29:13.080
[Guest]: So not only do politicians wield a lot of power to trade regulation for bribes or campaign

00:29:13.080 --> 00:29:18.880
[Guest]: finance, but then they can also make a lot of money through these extractive routes.

00:29:18.880 --> 00:29:22.880
[Guest]: So that was the story, you know, of a guy like Madhu Koda and Jharkhand, right? I mean,

00:29:22.880 --> 00:29:27.760
[Guest]: that's essentially the game he played. But this happens at a much smaller scale as well.

00:29:27.760 --> 00:29:33.800
[Guest]: So I mean, the thing in Mumbai, obviously, is, you know, why do you have this labyrinthine

00:29:33.800 --> 00:29:38.800
[Guest]: structure of licenses and permits to do anything in real estate? Well, part of the reason is

00:29:38.800 --> 00:29:43.120
[Guest]: because the politicians and the bureaucrats who control that need to fund themselves.

00:29:43.120 --> 00:29:47.200
[Guest]: And so they're able to kind of say, look, let's do a deal, I'll give you something and

00:29:47.200 --> 00:29:48.600
[Amit Varma]: you give me something in return.

00:29:48.600 --> 00:29:51.000
[Amit Varma]: Sadanand Anandamurthy And you kind of talk about the different,

00:29:51.000 --> 00:29:56.120
[Amit Varma]: the three different kinds of rents. And obviously, the first of those is something that is pervasive

00:29:56.120 --> 00:29:59.840
[Amit Varma]: all through our history is probably a little more before 91, but it still exists, which

00:29:59.840 --> 00:30:05.760
[Amit Varma]: is essentially regulatory rent, which, you know, I've had a bunch of episodes on different

00:30:05.760 --> 00:30:10.200
[Amit Varma]: aspects of this, like restaurant regulation, for example, and so on. And it basically means,

00:30:10.200 --> 00:30:14.000
[Amit Varma]: every time you're paying a bribe to get something done, you're paying a sort of regulatory rent

00:30:14.000 --> 00:30:18.400
[Amit Varma]: or every time a business is paying a bribe to get a license, that's regulatory rent.

00:30:18.400 --> 00:30:22.880
[Amit Varma]: And that's, you know, you come to power, and you typically have a whole lot of these rents

00:30:22.880 --> 00:30:28.400
[Amit Varma]: at your disposal. So you spend x amount getting to power and you can make 3x or 4x when you're

00:30:28.400 --> 00:30:33.320
[Amit Varma]: in power and disperse patronage accordingly. But what's interesting is after 91, a new

00:30:33.320 --> 00:30:38.960
[Amit Varma]: kind of rent explodes, which is extractive rents and where you quoted Rajan where he

00:30:38.960 --> 00:30:44.040
[Amit Varma]: says that the license Raj has now become a resource Raj. And another interesting fact

00:30:44.040 --> 00:30:48.100
[Amit Varma]: that I sort of found in your book was that while the number of billionaires expanded

00:30:48.100 --> 00:30:55.520
[Amit Varma]: massively after 91, a significant percentage of them were in what you call rent thick sectors,

00:30:55.520 --> 00:31:01.120
[Amit Varma]: which is they are in a sense benefiting from that kind of what you'd call crony socialism.

00:31:01.120 --> 00:31:05.960
[Guest]: Is that correct? That's right. I mean, so this is work that Michael Walton, who's at

00:31:05.960 --> 00:31:10.440
[Guest]: the Kennedy School and others have done to basically track billionaires over time. Now,

00:31:10.440 --> 00:31:15.320
[Guest]: there has been a rise in billionaires in many countries. But one thing you notice about

00:31:15.320 --> 00:31:22.240
[Guest]: India in the post 90s period is a the number of billionaires relative to India's sort of

00:31:22.240 --> 00:31:28.040
[Guest]: per capita GDP. And the second is the sectoral breakdown of where they are. They are in these

00:31:28.040 --> 00:31:34.280
[Guest]: rent thick sectors. So again, things like construction, real estate, you know, petroleum,

00:31:34.280 --> 00:31:40.520
[Guest]: oil and gas. We think a lot about it billionaires, but in fact, that's not where the bulk of

00:31:40.520 --> 00:31:48.520
[Guest]: the action has been over the past, you know, quarter century. And so that became a sort

00:31:48.520 --> 00:31:51.280
[Guest]: of hallmark, I think, of India's political economy.

00:31:51.280 --> 00:31:56.680
[Amit Varma]: Right. And there's a third kind of rent you mentioned political rents. Explain that.

00:31:56.680 --> 00:32:04.640
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, I think here in political rents, I mean, obviously, there are two ways of looking

00:32:04.640 --> 00:32:13.680
[Guest]: at it. So one is, when you're a politician, you are in a position to kind of extract resources

00:32:13.680 --> 00:32:22.280
[Guest]: to, you know, further your own career. So the standard example is you're a politician

00:32:22.280 --> 00:32:28.760
[Guest]: who has access to inside information about where a highway is going to go. And so therefore

00:32:28.760 --> 00:32:34.400
[Guest]: you trade on that interest either directly because you've set up a firm or your family

00:32:34.400 --> 00:32:39.480
[Guest]: member set up a firm. And you know, one remarkable fact about India is there's really no conflict

00:32:39.480 --> 00:32:45.840
[Guest]: of interest statute at the federal level here. So, you know, even today, members of parliament

00:32:45.840 --> 00:32:50.920
[Guest]: who have business interests, the only people that they have to declare those interests

00:32:50.920 --> 00:32:55.520
[Guest]: to are the parliament secretariat and the Rajya Sabha and Lok Sabha. And those are private.

00:32:55.520 --> 00:33:00.360
[Guest]: So the secretariat knows, but the people don't actually know. So it becomes very, very easy

00:33:00.360 --> 00:33:04.640
[Guest]: to do that. And then the second, of course, aspect of political rents is this question

00:33:04.640 --> 00:33:11.960
[Guest]: of sort of, you know, campaign finance, right? And being able to accumulate resources in

00:33:11.960 --> 00:33:17.440
[Guest]: a way that gives you a leg up. And I think this is where the political parties, you know,

00:33:17.440 --> 00:33:22.720
[Guest]: come in. You know, there is this question of, well, what is it that attracts political

00:33:22.720 --> 00:33:28.400
[Guest]: parties to criminals, right? In many societies, if you knew someone was tainted or tarnished

00:33:28.400 --> 00:33:32.400
[Guest]: because of some serious criminal case, you would sort of hightail it in the opposite

00:33:32.400 --> 00:33:36.120
[Guest]: direction. But in India, they actually are falling over one another to try to recruit

00:33:36.120 --> 00:33:39.200
[Guest]: these people to contest on their party labels.

00:33:39.200 --> 00:33:42.120
[Amit Varma]: Sadanand And that will bring us to the second question,

00:33:42.120 --> 00:33:46.120
[Amit Varma]: which we'll come to after a short break. But before that, for those of my listeners who

00:33:46.120 --> 00:33:51.520
[Amit Varma]: want an illustration of the first aspect of political rents that Milan just spoke about,

00:33:51.520 --> 00:33:56.160
[Amit Varma]: consider the Bangalore airport. Why is it so incredibly far from the city? Just look

00:33:56.160 --> 00:34:00.520
[Amit Varma]: into who bought all the land around it before the location was announced. We'll be back

