[Unknown]: is joined by a special guest on this one. And with that, let's continue with your show.

00:35:04.680 --> 00:35:07.620
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene in the unseen. I'm chatting with the political scientist Milan

00:35:07.620 --> 00:35:12.680
[Amit Varma]: Vaishnav on crime in politics. Why is there so much crime in Indian politics? And we take

00:35:12.680 --> 00:35:16.800
[Amit Varma]: it so much for granted that honestly, if there wasn't so much crime in Indian politics would

00:35:16.800 --> 00:35:21.520
[Amit Varma]: be a little surprise, right? So, you know, we've already looked at sort of the first

00:35:21.520 --> 00:35:25.360
[Amit Varma]: question that you raised, or what are the incentives for criminals to come into politics?

00:35:25.360 --> 00:35:29.280
[Amit Varma]: And it's because vertical integration, they want to look after the interests and all these

00:35:29.280 --> 00:35:33.960
[Amit Varma]: rents to be made, regulatory rents, extractive rents, political rents. It's an absolute no

00:35:33.960 --> 00:35:37.280
[Amit Varma]: brainer, you know, power brings money. If you're already a criminal, you want more of

00:35:37.280 --> 00:35:42.600
[Amit Varma]: it and as much as you can. And why experience it second hand or third hand, just get the

00:35:42.600 --> 00:35:48.240
[Amit Varma]: real thing. But why do parties pick criminals as a candidates?

00:35:48.240 --> 00:35:53.320
[Guest]: So I think to understand the answer that question, you have to go back and think about how the

00:35:53.320 --> 00:36:00.800
[Guest]: landscape has changed in recent decades. And one of the most striking changes has been

00:36:00.800 --> 00:36:05.240
[Guest]: the growth in the cost of elections, right? And the cost of elections has grown for numerous

00:36:05.240 --> 00:36:11.820
[Guest]: reasons. One is just population growth, right? The second is the competitiveness of elections

00:36:11.820 --> 00:36:17.540
[Guest]: has really increased over time. If you just look at the margins of victory in state and

00:36:17.540 --> 00:36:20.920
[Guest]: national elections, you know, they've come down quite significantly over time as the

00:36:20.920 --> 00:36:26.960
[Guest]: political landscape has become more, more crowded. Voters also have certain expectations

00:36:26.960 --> 00:36:31.800
[Guest]: in most places, as many of your listeners in India would certainly know on the eve of

00:36:31.800 --> 00:36:37.400
[Guest]: elections, parties and candidates fan out across the country and provide all kinds of

00:36:37.400 --> 00:36:42.760
[Guest]: goodies. It could be cash or liquor, the two most common as a way of trying to woo voters

00:36:42.760 --> 00:36:48.760
[Guest]: to their side. And now we also have a multiplicity of elections, you know, when there are 3 million

00:36:48.760 --> 00:36:53.640
[Guest]: elected panchayat officials in the country, right? So there's been an explosion in the

00:36:53.640 --> 00:36:58.920
[Guest]: number of elections. And so all of these things are kind of interacting. Now, here's where

00:36:58.920 --> 00:37:03.840
[Guest]: we come back to rents. You know, parties are facing this fiscal crunch of how do we meet

00:37:03.840 --> 00:37:09.080
[Guest]: this this financial challenge, but they don't want to necessarily dedicate themselves to

00:37:09.080 --> 00:37:14.240
[Guest]: the hard work of building party organizations, you know, recruiting members who are going

00:37:14.240 --> 00:37:19.760
[Guest]: to fund and so on and so forth. And so they've been increasingly thrust into the embrace

00:37:19.760 --> 00:37:25.000
[Guest]: of self financing candidates. Now, self financing candidates, as the name suggests, are people

00:37:25.000 --> 00:37:29.280
[Guest]: who can fund their own campaigns, but they can do more than that. They would pay parties

00:37:29.280 --> 00:37:36.120
[Guest]: for the privilege of running. They would perhaps fund or endow candidates on the same party

00:37:36.120 --> 00:37:40.840
[Guest]: label who don't have their own resources. They might, you know, willingly engage or

00:37:40.840 --> 00:37:45.640
[Guest]: certainly at least look the other way if there's other kind of rent seeking going on. And so

00:37:45.640 --> 00:37:52.760
[Guest]: this is, you know, the match that's been made between political parties and wealthy candidates.

00:37:52.760 --> 00:37:56.320
[Guest]: Now the question is where do criminals come in? Because, you know, an obvious question

00:37:56.320 --> 00:38:01.360
[Guest]: as well. You know, there are a lot of people in India with money, right? I mean, there's

00:38:01.360 --> 00:38:04.840
[Guest]: celebrities, there's film stars, there's cricketeers, there's whatever.

00:38:04.840 --> 00:38:05.840
[Amit Varma]: Not podcasters.

00:38:05.840 --> 00:38:13.040
[Guest]: Not podcasters or political scientists for that matter. And, you know, one thing that

00:38:13.040 --> 00:38:19.200
[Guest]: criminals have is A, they have liquid resources. So both the means and the know how of how

00:38:19.200 --> 00:38:25.600
[Guest]: to move money. The second is they have a kind of organizational platform because they tend

00:38:25.600 --> 00:38:31.280
[Guest]: to be deeply embedded in the constituencies which they've come to represent, right? So

00:38:31.280 --> 00:38:39.160
[Guest]: they have those networks of people and personnel and supporters already at hand. And of course

00:38:39.160 --> 00:38:44.040
[Guest]: there's some incentive for them in terms of protection to become part of the state. Now

00:38:44.040 --> 00:38:50.120
[Guest]: in India there is no formal immunity if you've been charged, cheated with a crime or even

00:38:50.120 --> 00:38:54.560
[Guest]: indicted. The question of losing your seat only comes if you're convicted and even then

00:38:54.560 --> 00:38:59.200
[Guest]: there are loopholes. But of course everyone knows that once you hold a position of political

00:38:59.200 --> 00:39:06.300
[Guest]: power there are various formal and informal ways to derail or delay justice. So it could

00:39:06.300 --> 00:39:11.440
[Guest]: be getting an official transferred, you know, sort of threatening punitive action if a member

00:39:11.440 --> 00:39:17.600
[Guest]: of the state tries to come at you. So they have both parties and candidates sort of have

00:39:17.600 --> 00:39:19.920
[Amit Varma]: incentives to make this match work.

00:39:19.920 --> 00:39:26.440
[Amit Varma]: I don't know why my mind suddenly went to a fellow Amit. But leaving that aside, I write

00:39:26.440 --> 00:39:29.640
[Amit Varma]: limericks for the Times of India and one that I rather like that I've written for them a

00:39:29.640 --> 00:39:34.520
[Amit Varma]: long time back is called politics and it kind of it's illustrates what you say. A Neta who

00:39:34.520 --> 00:39:39.280
[Amit Varma]: loves currency notes told me what his line of work denotes. It is kind of funny. We steal

00:39:39.280 --> 00:39:44.080
[Amit Varma]: people's money and we use some of it to buy their votes. And one of the interesting questions

00:39:44.080 --> 00:39:48.160
[Amit Varma]: I had about this, which a book points out is that everything is secret ballot. So you

00:39:48.160 --> 00:39:53.040
[Amit Varma]: could bribe a voter. But I always used to wonder that why is it that he will then, you

00:39:53.040 --> 00:39:58.880
[Amit Varma]: know, take a bribe from party X and not just vote for party Y. And what your book sort

00:39:58.880 --> 00:40:03.780
[Amit Varma]: of pointed out is that look, you know, parties know this that, you know, just by paying money

00:40:03.780 --> 00:40:08.000
[Amit Varma]: to a voter, they're not necessarily getting the vote, but it becomes a hygiene factor.

00:40:08.000 --> 00:40:11.420
[Amit Varma]: They know for sure that if they don't give him money, they're not getting their vote.

00:40:11.420 --> 00:40:16.160
[Amit Varma]: So they have to pay money anyway as a kind of hygiene factor. And over time, a sort of

00:40:16.160 --> 00:40:20.720
[Amit Varma]: Lake Wobegon effect kicks in and everybody has to pay more and more and campaign finance

00:40:20.720 --> 00:40:24.660
[Amit Varma]: just goes through the roof. And and then what do you do, you know, and these self financing

00:40:24.660 --> 00:40:30.360
[Amit Varma]: candidates come in and just take over the whole process. This so this is fundamentally

00:40:30.360 --> 00:40:34.320
[Guest]: the one big reason, right? Yeah, I mean, I think, look, we've done ourselves a great

00:40:34.320 --> 00:40:39.200
[Guest]: disservice by harping on this term vote buying, because it's not an accurate description of

00:40:39.200 --> 00:40:43.960
[Guest]: what's going on. I would prefer gift giving, because the idea that you could buy votes

00:40:43.960 --> 00:40:48.480
[Guest]: is that there's some ironclad contract that you could sign with the voter saying, look,

00:40:48.480 --> 00:40:52.280
[Guest]: I'm going to give you 500 bucks, and you're going to vote for me. Now, as you said, with

00:40:52.280 --> 00:40:56.920
[Guest]: the secret ballot, if I'm a savvy voter, I'm getting 500 bucks from from you and the next

00:40:56.920 --> 00:41:01.880
[Guest]: guy and three other people, and then I'll vote my conscience. But what politicians believe

00:41:01.880 --> 00:41:09.520
[Guest]: is that if they don't give money, there certainly will lose. So money doesn't buy you victory,

00:41:09.520 --> 00:41:13.800
[Guest]: it buys you a seat at the table. So the analogy that I use, it's it's sort of like playing

00:41:13.800 --> 00:41:17.840
[Guest]: poker, right? If you're playing poker with your friends, and you want to get dealt a

00:41:17.840 --> 00:41:21.640
[Guest]: stack of cards, you've got to Annie up, you've got to put something in the pot. Now, just

00:41:21.640 --> 00:41:25.080
[Guest]: because you've ended up and you've given some money doesn't mean you'll win, but you have

00:41:25.080 --> 00:41:30.120
[Guest]: no shot at winning if you don't do that, because you won't be at the table, right? And so it's

00:41:30.120 --> 00:41:34.560
[Guest]: a it's a kind of a classic prisoner's dilemma, right? Everyone would be better off if you

00:41:34.560 --> 00:41:40.280
[Guest]: cooperated and didn't give money. But the risks of defection are so high, that if I

00:41:40.280 --> 00:41:45.240
[Guest]: choose not to give and Amit gives, then he's now at a competitive advantage.

00:41:45.240 --> 00:41:48.520
[Amit Varma]: So I was actually a professional poker player for five years and a winning player. Did you

00:41:48.520 --> 00:41:52.360
[Guest]: know this? I did not know this. Yeah. So let me so why are you doing podcasts now?

00:41:52.360 --> 00:41:56.840
[Amit Varma]: Oh, well, long story, which I've spoken about on another podcast, you've appeared on Cyrus

00:41:56.840 --> 00:42:02.000
[Amit Varma]: says, but just to sort of, if you'll allow me to counter what you just said, I think

00:42:02.000 --> 00:42:05.480
[Amit Varma]: gift giving is a bit of a euphemism. I'd say it is what buying and here's why, of course,

00:42:05.480 --> 00:42:10.960
[Amit Varma]: they won't get the vote. But let's say they don't give the voter money, the probability

00:42:10.960 --> 00:42:15.240
[Amit Varma]: of getting a vote is zero. If they give the voter money, the probability is non zero,

00:42:15.240 --> 00:42:19.800
[Amit Varma]: let's say maybe it's point 2.3, whatever. So they're buying point 2.3 of a vote, that's

00:42:19.800 --> 00:42:24.560
[Amit Varma]: the expected value. So I'd still call it what buying except that it's not a full vote. It's

00:42:24.560 --> 00:42:29.160
[Guest]: a non zero. Yeah, I think that's that's a fair way of looking at it. Right. But, you

00:42:29.160 --> 00:42:34.160
[Guest]: know, there are some places in the world and there's a lot of research from Argentina and

00:42:34.160 --> 00:42:40.200
[Guest]: other Latin American countries where local party machines are quite strong. So you're

00:42:40.200 --> 00:42:45.560
[Guest]: able to monitor with some degree of measurement error what voters actually do on election

00:42:45.560 --> 00:42:51.680
[Guest]: day. And so therefore, you know, that kind of quid pro quo might be easier to consummate.

00:42:51.680 --> 00:42:56.440
[Amit Varma]: I just think it is lower. I think in India, it's lower. Right. Moving on from there. I

00:42:56.440 --> 00:43:00.200
[Amit Varma]: mean, it's so far is fairly logical that okay, you know, obviously, criminals want to get

00:43:00.200 --> 00:43:04.600
[Amit Varma]: into politics. Power is money. The Indian state has so much power and discretion that

00:43:04.600 --> 00:43:09.220
[Amit Varma]: it's just a source of unlimited rents. And political parties, which are the intermediaries

00:43:09.220 --> 00:43:15.120
[Amit Varma]: between in the marketplace between candidates and voters to exist, they need money to fight

00:43:15.120 --> 00:43:19.040
[Amit Varma]: elections, they need money, self financing candidates are the best. And, you know, if

00:43:19.040 --> 00:43:23.480
[Amit Varma]: a candidate finances himself, he is effectively subsidizing others, like you pointed out in

00:43:23.480 --> 00:43:28.080
[Amit Varma]: your book, because the opportunity cost of the money and so on. The big question here

00:43:28.080 --> 00:43:34.960
[Amit Varma]: is that, you know, we are in a democracy, why do informed voters actually choose to

00:43:34.960 --> 00:43:39.480
[Amit Varma]: vote for criminal politicians? In fact, one of the most surprising statistics in your

00:43:39.480 --> 00:43:45.680
[Amit Varma]: book was that if you are a criminal, your chances of winning an election are far higher

00:43:45.680 --> 00:43:50.880
[Amit Varma]: than that of a non criminal. It is clearly a feature, not a bug. Why do voters vote for

00:43:50.880 --> 00:43:57.720
[Guest]: criminals? Right. So I think just to rewind for one second, if you look at this association

00:43:57.720 --> 00:44:06.080
[Guest]: between money and criminality, what you see is that money, rich politicians do seem to

00:44:06.080 --> 00:44:11.560
[Guest]: be disproportionately rewarded. But criminal politicians who are rich seem to have an additional

00:44:11.560 --> 00:44:15.920
[Guest]: bump. So if money were doing all the work, then criminality shouldn't matter. So clearly

00:44:15.920 --> 00:44:20.160
[Guest]: there's something above and beyond. There's a delta there that's benefiting criminals.

00:44:20.160 --> 00:44:24.440
[Guest]: So what is that? And that's where I think the voters come into play. So, you know, I

00:44:24.440 --> 00:44:30.160
[Guest]: think there's kind of two cardinal facts about how Indian politics tend to operate, right?

00:44:30.160 --> 00:44:37.120
[Guest]: So one is that in many parts of this country, the rule of law is quite weak. And what I

00:44:37.120 --> 00:44:43.840
[Guest]: mean by that is that the government is not seen as an impartial or credible provider

00:44:43.840 --> 00:44:50.360
[Guest]: of kind of core state functions, right? So what public goods delivery, law and order,

00:44:50.360 --> 00:44:56.880
[Guest]: justice and so on. So that's one. There's a vacuum there. Now, number two is that obviously

00:44:56.880 --> 00:45:03.760
[Guest]: we know that identity politics and social divisions are a prominent feature of Indian

00:45:03.760 --> 00:45:08.480
[Guest]: politics and that it varies from place to place. In some places, the divisions or the

00:45:08.480 --> 00:45:14.280
[Guest]: contestation between caste groups and communities may be less or may be more. But in those places

00:45:14.280 --> 00:45:20.960
[Guest]: where the rule of law is weak and those social divisions are highly salient, criminals are

00:45:20.960 --> 00:45:26.600
[Guest]: able to use their criminality essentially as a sign of their credibility to get things

00:45:26.600 --> 00:45:32.200
[Guest]: done for their constituents, right? So they're basically able to say, if you support me,

00:45:32.200 --> 00:45:39.080
[Guest]: I'll be able to do your work by hook or crook. Now, the pitch they're making is not necessarily

00:45:39.080 --> 00:45:45.080
[Guest]: to the constituency at large. It's primarily to their own caste or community and those

00:45:45.080 --> 00:45:50.640
[Guest]: allied groups, right? And because we're in a first-past-the-post system, you know, you

00:45:50.640 --> 00:45:56.600
[Guest]: can win an election with 25 or 30 percent of the vote. So you don't have to cater to

00:45:56.600 --> 00:46:01.580
[Guest]: the median voter, right? If you could get your group and a few others on board, then

00:46:01.580 --> 00:46:07.120
[Guest]: you could cross the finish line first. So in some ways, the electoral system also creates,

00:46:07.120 --> 00:46:15.200
[Guest]: you know, further incentives. So this kind of reverses the usual logic of information

00:46:15.200 --> 00:46:22.320
[Guest]: on its head, right? Which is voters actually know and candidates who are criminals have

00:46:22.320 --> 00:46:27.000
[Guest]: an incentive to advertise that they have these characteristics because it's seen as an asset

00:46:27.000 --> 00:46:28.720
[Guest]: and many parts are not a liability.

00:46:28.720 --> 00:46:32.360
[Amit Varma]: Just to sort of then unpack those two points. The first point is, of course, there's no

00:46:32.360 --> 00:46:36.720
[Amit Varma]: – the rule of law in large parts of this country is completely absent. It's an illusion.

00:46:36.720 --> 00:46:41.520
[Amit Varma]: And government, it's said, often begins as a protection racket. And when the government

00:46:41.520 --> 00:46:45.760
[Amit Varma]: doesn't do its job of, you know, being a credible protection racket, you have competing protection

00:46:45.760 --> 00:46:51.280
[Amit Varma]: rackets coming in, which may or may not, you know, divide along lines of ethnicity or caste

00:46:51.280 --> 00:46:56.720
[Amit Varma]: or identity or whatever. So the first fundamental function that a lot of these criminal groups

00:46:56.720 --> 00:47:01.440
[Amit Varma]: do is that, listen, there is no law and order here. And I am the law and order. And this

00:47:01.440 --> 00:47:05.400
[Amit Varma]: is something again, you point out with a bunch of concrete examples in your book, whether

00:47:05.400 --> 00:47:09.200
[Amit Varma]: it's Mohammed Shah, Shahabuddin, or other people, where people often say about them

00:47:09.200 --> 00:47:13.320
[Amit Varma]: that look, okay, you know, he might have all these criminal activities through his name,

00:47:13.320 --> 00:47:17.480
[Amit Varma]: but he looks after us. You know, these are all of the things that he does for us. And

00:47:17.480 --> 00:47:21.580
[Amit Varma]: when they list them out, you realize that, you know, this is a gap created by the absence

00:47:21.580 --> 00:47:25.520
[Amit Varma]: of the state, the state can't provide all of this, whether it's little things like conflict

00:47:25.520 --> 00:47:29.720
[Amit Varma]: resolution, or whether it's basic communities, these are guys coming and saying, Okay, I'll

00:47:29.720 --> 00:47:34.880
[Amit Varma]: take care of all of you. So it's not just a gunda becoming the dada, but taking the

00:47:34.880 --> 00:47:39.440
[Amit Varma]: place of the state in a sense, and therefore getting that respect from the community that

00:47:39.440 --> 00:47:43.040
[Amit Varma]: this is a guy who does everything and therefore they can win the election and make the additional

00:47:43.040 --> 00:47:44.040
[Guest]: rents that there are.

00:47:44.040 --> 00:47:47.520
[Guest]: Yeah, and I think there's a variety of ways that they can do this. So I talked about that

00:47:47.520 --> 00:47:52.040
[Guest]: in the book. So you know, the one thing is sort of intervening in the administration

00:47:52.040 --> 00:47:58.680
[Guest]: and distribution of welfare benefits, right? You are denied a BPL card, the BDO, block

00:47:58.680 --> 00:48:03.480
[Guest]: development officer in your locality is not paying attention. I contact my politician,

00:48:03.480 --> 00:48:07.400
[Guest]: he threatens to, you know, knock a couple heads together and all of a sudden I get my

00:48:07.400 --> 00:48:12.080
[Guest]: BPL card. So there's something around kind of welfare and administration. Law and order

00:48:12.080 --> 00:48:18.040
[Guest]: security is another one, right? I mean, in many places, you go to a police house and

00:48:18.040 --> 00:48:21.120
[Guest]: you are saying, Look, I've been a victim of a crime and they just you know, if you're

00:48:21.120 --> 00:48:27.040
[Guest]: not the right profile, then you won't get an FIR filed. But again, that's worth someone

00:48:27.040 --> 00:48:32.240
[Guest]: who can throw their weight around to make that work done, get that work done as a benefit.

00:48:32.240 --> 00:48:38.800
[Guest]: Similar stories with justice, right? We know that the judiciary in India has so many weaknesses,

00:48:38.800 --> 00:48:45.320
[Guest]: especially at the local level. And so therefore, if you have a neighborly dispute with someone

00:48:45.320 --> 00:48:50.120
[Guest]: who's in your area, you could go to the courts, but you may be waiting decades for a verdict.

00:48:50.120 --> 00:48:55.480
[Guest]: So if you go to a strongman who's able to enforce a decision, even if he rules against

00:48:55.480 --> 00:49:01.160
[Guest]: you, at least he's decided, right? And there's sort of some finality. The fourth thing is,

00:49:01.160 --> 00:49:06.480
[Guest]: I think, is a kind of social insurance function. You know, I mean, especially for households

00:49:06.480 --> 00:49:11.880
[Guest]: who are hovering around the poverty line, any one shock, it could be a death in the

00:49:11.880 --> 00:49:16.400
[Guest]: family, it could be an illness, it could be a marriage, right, where you have to come

00:49:16.400 --> 00:49:22.560
[Guest]: up with dowry payments, you need someone that you can turn to in your kind of hour of need.

00:49:22.560 --> 00:49:25.800
[Guest]: And that's another thing that these criminal candidates are quite good at. So one of the

00:49:25.800 --> 00:49:30.040
[Guest]: things you often hear when you interview their voters is, you know, you paid for my daughter's

00:49:30.040 --> 00:49:36.560
[Guest]: wedding, right? Or I had to take care of expenses after my mother died. And I didn't know who

00:49:36.560 --> 00:49:39.520
[Guest]: to turn to because I didn't have access to formal credit.

00:49:39.520 --> 00:49:44.120
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. And one of the, you know, in your book, there's a stroke of this politician who claims

00:49:44.120 --> 00:49:49.520
[Amit Varma]: he funded, you know, 10,000 marriages, I think, in a particular area himself. And there's

00:49:49.520 --> 00:49:53.040
[Amit Varma]: an interesting defense of the same guy, if I remember by someone speaking to you and

00:49:53.040 --> 00:49:56.440
[Amit Varma]: saying, Listen, he didn't actually murder anyone, he just ordered them.

00:49:56.440 --> 00:50:03.440
[Guest]: Yeah. So I this was a politician by the name of Anand Singh, who was a curious figure,

00:50:03.440 --> 00:50:10.600
[Guest]: because at the time I went and saw him, this was 2010 in Bihar. And this was when Nitish

00:50:10.600 --> 00:50:15.880
[Guest]: Kumar had this sort of governance revolution, you know, after the what they call the 15

00:50:15.880 --> 00:50:21.160
[Guest]: years of jungle Raj, you know, under Lallu Prasad Yadav and Rabri Devi. And here was

00:50:21.160 --> 00:50:29.440
[Guest]: this good governance, Chief Minister, who was, you know, patronizing this gunda politician

00:50:29.440 --> 00:50:34.280
[Guest]: Anand Singh, partially because he represented a very important sort of caste community,

00:50:34.280 --> 00:50:40.640
[Guest]: the Bhoomi hars in central Bihar. And so I'd gone to see sort of a, you know, kind of educated

00:50:40.640 --> 00:50:45.520
[Guest]: engineer who was a friend of a friend who lived in Anand Singh's constituency. And I

00:50:45.520 --> 00:50:48.680
[Guest]: was pressing him on, you know, why would you vote for someone like this? And, you know,

00:50:48.680 --> 00:50:53.440
[Guest]: I read today in the Times of India that he's wanted on sexual assault charters and murder

00:50:53.440 --> 00:51:00.040
[Guest]: cases and you know, all these really pretty nefarious things. And, and, and then he had

00:51:00.040 --> 00:51:07.320
[Guest]: this insight, which is, you know, you misunderstand, you know, Anand Singh isn't a murderer, he

00:51:07.320 --> 00:51:12.360
[Guest]: merely manages murder. And that's where the protection racket really hit me, right? I

00:51:12.360 --> 00:51:18.600
[Guest]: mean, what he was saying is, Anand Singh is the CEO of my local protection racket, and

00:51:18.600 --> 00:51:24.840
[Guest]: I'm one of the people who's being protected. So if I want the guys over there, you know,

00:51:24.840 --> 00:51:28.840
[Guest]: sort of figuratively pointing towards the, you know, backward caste community, the other

00:51:28.840 --> 00:51:33.920
[Guest]: community which is gaining ground, if I want them to take over my land and my house, then

00:51:33.920 --> 00:51:40.760
[Guest]: I can vote for a Mr. Clean politician. But as, as you know, until law and order gets

00:51:40.760 --> 00:51:45.400
[Guest]: sorted, you know, I'm going to need my, my protection, and he's the one who's doing it.

00:51:45.400 --> 00:51:49.520
[Guest]: So you're calling him coming from the big city and calling him a criminal, but I see

00:51:49.520 --> 00:51:50.520
[Guest]: him as necessary.

00:51:50.520 --> 00:51:53.560
[Amit Varma]: Sadanand Rajanamurti And it's because of one protection racket

00:51:53.560 --> 00:51:58.640
[Amit Varma]: that we should be there, the legitimate protection racket of the state is absent, which is why

00:51:58.640 --> 00:52:02.120
[Amit Varma]: you have these sort of competing protection rackets and it's competing protection rackets,

00:52:02.120 --> 00:52:08.040
[Amit Varma]: because you're often, mostly in India, along ethnic lines or caste lines, or basically

00:52:08.040 --> 00:52:13.120
[Amit Varma]: along identity politics line, which with each sort of racket saying, hey, I look after my

00:52:13.120 --> 00:52:18.000
[Amit Varma]: people and it's like you quote Lalu Prasad in your book, where at one point he says,

00:52:18.000 --> 00:52:22.560
[Amit Varma]: vikas nahi samman chahiye, which was his, this thing, which is basically, we don't want

00:52:22.560 --> 00:52:27.600
[Amit Varma]: development, we want respect. And again, he's speaking for a bunch of, you know, castes,

00:52:27.600 --> 00:52:32.040
[Amit Varma]: which otherwise feel ignored. And that's what matters to them. Not so much development,

00:52:32.040 --> 00:52:36.040
[Amit Varma]: because hey, who believes in words like that, but just patronage, give patronage to our

00:52:36.040 --> 00:52:37.040
[Guest]: people.

00:52:37.040 --> 00:52:38.040
[Guest]: You know,

00:52:38.040 --> 00:52:46.600
[Guest]: I don't want to glorify these criminal politicians, because there's a central flaw in the story,

00:52:46.600 --> 00:52:53.840
[Guest]: which is, at the end of the day, these characters, yes, they may be providing something of value.

00:52:53.840 --> 00:52:58.960
[Guest]: And I think the fact that they're doing that, and or the perception that they're doing that

00:52:58.960 --> 00:53:07.600
[Guest]: is what gives them voter backing. But they don't have incentive to fundamentally fix

00:53:07.600 --> 00:53:14.440
[Guest]: what ails the state, because they are able to mobilize on the fact that the state doesn't

00:53:14.440 --> 00:53:20.120
[Guest]: work. And so you need me to help navigate it, right? You need me to get the charges

00:53:20.120 --> 00:53:25.360
[Guest]: filed at the police house, you need me to get the BPL card. Once you actually improve

00:53:25.360 --> 00:53:31.440
[Guest]: the state sufficiently, that intermediary's role disappears. And so they're interested

00:53:31.440 --> 00:53:36.920
[Guest]: typically in bandaid fixes, right? I'm not going to push for a whole scale reform of

00:53:36.920 --> 00:53:43.120
[Guest]: the police apparatus. I don't want to necessarily fix the welfare distribution system. I want

00:53:43.120 --> 00:53:48.600
[Guest]: to have an incentive to keep it broken, but then apply patches or band-aids where I see

00:53:48.600 --> 00:53:53.960
[Guest]: fit. So I think that's the one central flaw, which shouldn't be overlooked. And the second,

00:53:53.960 --> 00:53:59.760
[Guest]: again, just to reiterate, they're not necessarily interested in doing this for their constituency

00:53:59.760 --> 00:54:05.960
[Guest]: at large, right? I mean, they are very explicit that they function sort of like Robin Hoods,

00:54:05.960 --> 00:54:10.360
[Guest]: where you're not necessarily taking resources from the rich to pay the poor. You're taking

00:54:10.360 --> 00:54:15.000
[Guest]: resources from one community and redistributing it to another community. So I think those

00:54:15.000 --> 00:54:21.640
[Guest]: are there are all kinds of negative externalities from this kind of a transaction.

00:54:21.640 --> 00:54:25.160
[Amit Varma]: Sadaq Khan Which brings us to your fourth question. Like

00:54:25.160 --> 00:54:29.040
[Amit Varma]: we've looked at the three kinds of incentives so far incentives for the criminals to get

00:54:29.040 --> 00:54:33.800
[Amit Varma]: into politics, for the parties to pick criminals and for the voters to vote. And you know,

00:54:33.800 --> 00:54:37.560
[Amit Varma]: because there's no rule of law, because everyone is divided along identity lines, it makes

00:54:37.560 --> 00:54:42.160
[Amit Varma]: sense for them to vote for the local dada who look after their needs because there's

00:54:42.160 --> 00:54:48.040
[Amit Varma]: no other protection racket in town. How do we fix this? An even more fundamental philosophical

00:54:48.040 --> 00:54:52.440
[Amit Varma]: question that you asked before you bear you know, when you begin your chapter, much to

00:54:52.440 --> 00:54:57.320
[Amit Varma]: my gratification, because the question struck me as well, which is that if we are placing

00:54:57.320 --> 00:55:02.840
[Amit Varma]: a value on a democracy where people choose their leaders, the leaders they want, why

00:55:02.840 --> 00:55:03.840
[Amit Varma]: should we fix this?

00:55:03.840 --> 00:55:07.120
[Guest]: Dr. Ian Lamb Yeah, I mean, that sort of, I think, builds

00:55:07.120 --> 00:55:13.480
[Guest]: on what I just said before, which is, the election of criminals does solve a particular

00:55:13.480 --> 00:55:18.440
[Guest]: problem in terms of it allows people to have access to something that they may not have

00:55:18.440 --> 00:55:23.080
[Guest]: had before, right? Or, in some cases, even it's the promise of that access, they don't

00:55:23.080 --> 00:55:27.480
[Guest]: know that they'll need something now, but they may need it in the future. And so therefore,

00:55:27.480 --> 00:55:32.880
[Guest]: it's a kind of hedge against risk. But as I mentioned, there are these larger negative

00:55:32.880 --> 00:55:38.720
[Guest]: externalities, because the system will never sort of improve. So what do we do to fix it?

00:55:38.720 --> 00:55:44.080
[Guest]: You know, there, if you take the same kind of supply and demand function, or analogy

00:55:44.080 --> 00:55:50.760
[Guest]: that I discussed, so on the supply side, this really has to do with with money, right? How

00:55:50.760 --> 00:56:00.120
[Guest]: do you try to create a system such that money from private individuals plays less of a role?

00:56:00.120 --> 00:56:05.040
[Guest]: And so that gets fundamentally to campaign finance reform. Then when you get to the demand

00:56:05.040 --> 00:56:12.560
[Guest]: side, one of in the ways the most disheartening messages of the book is, I wish that this

00:56:12.560 --> 00:56:18.200
[Guest]: was just an information story. Because if this was just an information story of voters

00:56:18.200 --> 00:56:23.320
[Guest]: don't know how to tell a good type from a bad type, then you could invest in media,

00:56:23.320 --> 00:56:29.840
[Guest]: you could invest in civic activism, you could invest in voter education. But if these individuals

00:56:29.840 --> 00:56:35.000
[Guest]: are actually doing something which is both informed and rational, then you then you have

00:56:35.000 --> 00:56:42.160
[Guest]: a problem. And the only solution there is trying to find ways of building up the state

00:56:42.160 --> 00:56:48.040
[Guest]: capacity. And I think here, they're kind of two aspects, right? I think we often get into

00:56:48.040 --> 00:56:52.840
[Guest]: these very simplistic debates, not just in India, the United States and the EU everywhere

00:56:52.840 --> 00:56:57.400
[Guest]: about, you know, do we shrink the state? Do we grow the state? And you sort of have to

00:56:57.400 --> 00:57:03.400
[Guest]: do both at the same time. So the problem in India is that you have a bureaucracy that's

00:57:03.400 --> 00:57:07.960
[Guest]: over bureaucratized in procedural terms, right? So this is whether it's the ease of doing

00:57:07.960 --> 00:57:12.380
[Guest]: business or the ease of, you know, getting welfare benefits, everybody who's ever tried

00:57:12.380 --> 00:57:18.320
[Guest]: to interact with the Indian state knows that it's extremely difficult, costly, inefficient,

00:57:18.320 --> 00:57:23.440
[Guest]: and so on. So you have to kind of cut that fat. But at the same time, the Indian state

00:57:23.440 --> 00:57:28.200
[Guest]: has to build up its muscle. And what I mean by that is, even though it's over bureaucratized

00:57:28.200 --> 00:57:33.520
[Guest]: procedurally, it's highly undermanned in personnel terms, right? There are large parts of the

00:57:33.520 --> 00:57:38.520
[Guest]: bureaucratic apparatus, which simply not only don't have enough people, but they also don't

00:57:38.520 --> 00:57:43.040
[Guest]: have the right kinds of people or the people with the right skills. And so, you know, it's

00:57:43.040 --> 00:57:47.840
[Guest]: sort of a cute phrase. But the thing I say in the book is you kind of have to right size

00:57:47.840 --> 00:57:52.760
[Guest]: the state, right? Now, the trouble over there is this is a generational challenge, right?

00:57:52.760 --> 00:57:58.000
[Guest]: I mean, this is something that politicians will have to do, and then exceeds their limited

00:57:58.000 --> 00:58:00.400
[Guest]: time horizon of say, four or five years.

00:58:00.400 --> 00:58:03.240
[Amit Varma]: Sadanandam Bhaiyaan, Ph.D.: Yeah, and that's, in fact, an insight I first picked up from

00:58:03.240 --> 00:58:08.480
[Amit Varma]: Fukuyama that what India needs is a strong state that does a few things well, instead

00:58:08.480 --> 00:58:12.800
[Amit Varma]: of what we have now, which is a very large state that does everything badly. And, you

00:58:12.800 --> 00:58:16.880
[Amit Varma]: know, again, like you point out in the book, our problem is not people, we perhaps need

00:58:16.880 --> 00:58:20.920
[Amit Varma]: more people, our problem is procedures, there are too many procedures. And both of those

00:58:20.920 --> 00:58:27.200
[Amit Varma]: seem to strike at the heart of the incentives problem here. If you just have much less procedures,

00:58:27.200 --> 00:58:32.640
[Amit Varma]: much less licenses to give to people, much less discretion that government servants have,

00:58:32.640 --> 00:58:37.440
[Amit Varma]: then you immediately reduce rents available and therefore the incentives for criminals

00:58:37.440 --> 00:58:42.200
[Amit Varma]: to come into politics because hey, how do you profit? And at the same time, if you actually

00:58:42.200 --> 00:58:46.160
[Amit Varma]: strengthen your state where you need to, if you have a good rule of law, if you have good

00:58:46.160 --> 00:58:52.000
[Amit Varma]: police, if you have good conflict resolution and, you know, good, you fix the justice system,

00:58:52.000 --> 00:58:56.240
[Amit Varma]: then you don't need a protection racket apart from that because the state is doing its job

00:58:56.240 --> 00:59:01.720
[Amit Varma]: and then you change the incentives for the voters to act. But, you know, I mean, these

00:59:01.720 --> 00:59:06.640
[Amit Varma]: two are the obvious but very long-term fixes. And the problem with long-term fixes is that

00:59:06.640 --> 00:59:11.400
[Amit Varma]: politicians live for the short term. So what are their incentives? I mean, can changes

00:59:11.400 --> 00:59:13.840
[Amit Varma]: like this ever happen? They haven't for 71 years.

00:59:13.840 --> 00:59:18.240
[Guest]: Yeah. No, it's a good question. I mean, I think there's some good news and some bad

00:59:18.240 --> 00:59:27.000
[Guest]: news, right? So on the good news, you could say that, you know, as India is getting richer,

00:59:27.000 --> 00:59:33.520
[Guest]: as per capita incomes are rising, politicians in many states have stopped tinkering with

00:59:33.520 --> 00:59:39.640
[Guest]: the sort of petty corruption that most citizens have to interact with, right? So in some ways,

00:59:39.640 --> 00:59:44.040
[Guest]: this is the story of the southern states, right? In Tamil Nadu, the day-to-day state

00:59:44.040 --> 00:59:48.760
[Guest]: when it comes to kind of welfare and other things works pretty well, but because politicians

00:59:48.760 --> 00:59:53.800
[Guest]: are focused on larger rents, right? Larger rents about roads and ports and highways and

00:59:53.800 --> 00:59:59.200
[Guest]: extraction and so on. Now, one could say cynically, that's a sign of progress, right? You've kind

00:59:59.200 --> 01:00:03.080
[Guest]: of shifted from a blue collar corruption equilibrium to a white collar.

01:00:03.080 --> 01:00:04.920
[Guest]: At least the common man doesn't face a burden.

01:00:04.920 --> 01:00:11.600
[Guest]: At least the common man doesn't face a burden and, you know, just look at Andhra and Tamil

01:00:11.600 --> 01:00:17.360
[Guest]: Nadu in particular. I mean, it's virtually impossible to make it in politics if you aren't

01:00:17.360 --> 01:00:21.600
[Guest]: some kind of person involved in infrastructure or real estate, right? I mean, that's where

01:00:21.600 --> 01:00:29.280
[Guest]: the – it's most noticeable. So the flippant sort of thing I talk about, I guess it's

01:00:29.280 --> 01:00:33.480
[Guest]: not in the book, but what I was thinking about, which is a kind of film analogy is, you know,

01:00:33.480 --> 01:00:38.640
[Guest]: sort of like the transition from Godfather I to Godfather III, right? I mean, how do

01:00:38.640 --> 01:00:43.840
[Guest]: you essentially legitimize yourself that you move away from kind of ordinary corruption

01:00:43.840 --> 01:00:49.880
[Guest]: to try to actually, you know, make money in a maybe perhaps less corrupt or less distortionary

01:00:49.880 --> 01:00:54.640
[Guest]: way for kind of the average person? And I think that's the sort of trajectory that

01:00:54.640 --> 01:00:56.440
[Guest]: maybe India is on. So that's one.

01:00:56.440 --> 01:01:00.080
[Guest]: The second is, you know, the middle class is very absent. And I think one of the big

01:01:00.080 --> 01:01:06.200
[Guest]: stories about post-independence India is how the middle class has really exited from mainstream

01:01:06.200 --> 01:01:10.200
[Guest]: politics. You know, I think many people who were in the middle class were disappointed

01:01:10.200 --> 01:01:14.360
[Guest]: with what the state could do and then realized that they had private alternatives, whether

01:01:14.360 --> 01:01:23.200
[Guest]: it's schools, water, education, healthcare, security. And so how do we re-engage that

01:01:23.200 --> 01:01:28.680
[Guest]: part of the citizenry to say, look, this matters for you? Because at some point, you have to

01:01:28.680 --> 01:01:33.280
[Guest]: step outside of your bubble and deal with, you know, the central problem of the state.

01:01:33.280 --> 01:01:37.720
[Guest]: And that's, you know, historically, I think, in many societies, what has helped to kind

01:01:37.720 --> 01:01:45.040
[Guest]: of push reform. And then crisis, right? I mean, when you see or have either economic

01:01:45.040 --> 01:01:50.440
[Guest]: crises or corruption scandals, right, they tend to introduce some kind of turn in the

01:01:50.440 --> 01:01:54.560
[Guest]: system. Now, unfortunately, you don't want to wait for a crisis to happen to have to

01:01:54.560 --> 01:01:58.840
[Guest]: do reform. But I think empirically, that's often what we see.

01:01:58.840 --> 01:02:02.520
[Amit Varma]: Some would argue we are in the middle of an ongoing crisis. It's like a frog in boiling

01:02:02.520 --> 01:02:07.200
[Amit Varma]: water. You don't notice the temperature getting higher. Of course, that's an apocryphal story.

01:02:07.200 --> 01:02:12.440
[Amit Varma]: The frog will actually jump out if the water reaches a certain temperature. And the interesting

01:02:12.440 --> 01:02:15.760
[Amit Varma]: thing about the second point you made is that India's middle class has actually grown massively

01:02:15.760 --> 01:02:20.360
[Amit Varma]: since liberalization. So you'd expect that, you know, earlier, one reason for the apathy

01:02:20.360 --> 01:02:24.080
[Amit Varma]: could have been that, you know, what difference does it make if I go and vote? It makes absolutely

01:02:24.080 --> 01:02:28.520
[Amit Varma]: no difference. But now that's changed. But then, you know, people respond to crisis in

01:02:28.520 --> 01:02:33.120
[Amit Varma]: different ways. And it's not necessary that everyone will want these long term kind of

01:02:33.120 --> 01:02:36.360
[Amit Varma]: solutions. What you also say in your book is that a lot of the short term solutions

01:02:36.360 --> 01:02:40.720
[Amit Varma]: which people come up with just don't work and might even be dangerous. Tell me a little

01:02:40.720 --> 01:02:41.720
[Guest]: bit about that.

01:02:41.720 --> 01:02:49.680
[Guest]: Well, you know, I think if you take the justice system, for example, everybody's favorite

01:02:49.680 --> 01:02:54.880
[Guest]: remedy for what ails the justice system is fast track courts, right? And so we saw this

01:02:54.880 --> 01:03:01.920
[Guest]: after the horrific gang rape in Delhi in 2012. We this even got gets talked about in the

01:03:01.920 --> 01:03:06.200
[Guest]: context of criminal politicians that can't you just set up fast track courts and I talk

01:03:06.200 --> 01:03:11.740
[Guest]: about that in the book as well. But what you see from studies of these courts is that eventually

01:03:11.740 --> 01:03:17.640
[Guest]: they just succumb to the larger pathologies of the justice system. That's one problem.

01:03:17.640 --> 01:03:21.360
[Guest]: The second problem is by giving fast justice to someone, you're necessarily giving slow

01:03:21.360 --> 01:03:28.680
[Guest]: justice to someone else. You know, I think this is a really hard nut to crack because

01:03:28.680 --> 01:03:34.160
[Guest]: politicians are able to occupy this gray space where they're able to say, look, I've been

01:03:34.160 --> 01:03:40.560
[Guest]: charged with a crime, but I haven't been convicted of one yet. And in this country, we have the

01:03:40.560 --> 01:03:45.840
[Guest]: rule of law which says, look, there's a presumption of innocence until being proven guilty. And

01:03:45.840 --> 01:03:51.520
[Guest]: they're right. Now, on the other hand, given the infirmities of the justice system, they

01:03:51.520 --> 01:03:57.200
[Guest]: also know that they can wait this out. So, you know, if we go back to the case of Anand

01:03:57.200 --> 01:04:03.120
[Guest]: Singh, who was the CEO of the protection racket, the the management of murder, not the murder,

01:04:03.120 --> 01:04:09.920
[Guest]: you know, he had dozens of cases that went back literally decades, and none of them had

01:04:09.920 --> 01:04:16.840
[Guest]: ever come to any kind of conclusion because, you know, judges passed on, prosecutors were

01:04:16.840 --> 01:04:22.320
[Guest]: transferred evidence, you know, literally went up missing, witnesses got got cold feet.

01:04:22.320 --> 01:04:28.520
[Guest]: And so the solution to the problem is kind of inherent in the nature of the problem itself.

01:04:28.520 --> 01:04:35.880
[Amit Varma]: Right. Your fifth question, finally, which is what is the impact of this on democracy?

01:04:35.880 --> 01:04:41.240
[Guest]: So you know, here, I think there's a couple of ways of looking at it. I mean, I think

01:04:41.240 --> 01:04:49.920
[Guest]: one is that, in some ways, you know, criminality is a byproduct of how democracy has been functioning

01:04:49.920 --> 01:04:53.960
[Guest]: in a weakly institutionalized setting. You know, I think there's some people who would

01:04:53.960 --> 01:05:02.040
[Guest]: prefer to consider this phenomenon, as you know, these are a bunch of sub national, authoritarian

01:05:02.040 --> 01:05:08.280
[Guest]: figures who are going around coercing voters and manipulating results. And that's how they're

01:05:08.280 --> 01:05:13.680
[Guest]: able to win. I don't find that framing to be very helpful, because, you know, in many

01:05:13.680 --> 01:05:20.000
[Guest]: cases, these are people who are will winning some of the most competitive elections anywhere

01:05:20.000 --> 01:05:26.560
[Guest]: in the world. And they're doing that. Because voters vote for them, and again, believe that

01:05:26.560 --> 01:05:30.600
[Guest]: they're making a rational calculation, it may not be the first best solution, right?

01:05:30.600 --> 01:05:35.360
[Guest]: I mean, voters are not stupid, they Yeah, it'd be great to have a clean politician.

01:05:35.360 --> 01:05:40.160
[Guest]: But given what's around us, I don't think that that's necessarily going to pay off for

01:05:40.160 --> 01:05:48.800
[Guest]: the here and the now. So I think the larger potential fallout from this is, does it start

01:05:48.800 --> 01:05:56.760
[Guest]: to erode people's perceptions of democracy and the rule of law? Do they start to say,

01:05:56.760 --> 01:06:02.680
[Guest]: well, this particular politician is able to get away literally with murder? And so therefore,

01:06:02.680 --> 01:06:08.960
[Guest]: you know, why should a different set of rules, you know, apply to me? And, you know, I think

01:06:08.960 --> 01:06:14.200
[Guest]: here to, you know, this is where money comes in, right? If people literally think that,

01:06:14.200 --> 01:06:18.680
[Guest]: you know, look, I mean, you could buy or sell elections, then forget about it, I'm just

01:06:18.680 --> 01:06:22.880
[Guest]: going to retreat, and you end up with voter apathy, or you just get up with this very

01:06:22.880 --> 01:06:29.800
[Guest]: cynical kind of notion of special interest politics. So, so again, it's a good news,

01:06:29.800 --> 01:06:34.160
[Guest]: bad news story, which in some sense, these people are products of democracy, but they're

01:06:34.160 --> 01:06:40.600
[Guest]: creating a kind of partial accountability that has lots of other, you know, negative

01:06:40.600 --> 01:06:41.600
[Guest]: consequences.

01:06:41.600 --> 01:06:45.240
[Amit Varma]: Sadaq Khan So I'm going to kind of end with a standard

01:06:45.240 --> 01:06:51.200
[Amit Varma]: question, which I ask all of my guests on the subject of the choice, which is not about

01:06:51.200 --> 01:06:56.200
[Amit Varma]: crime in politics, but about democracy in general, Indian democracy in general, what

01:06:56.200 --> 01:07:00.920
[Amit Varma]: makes you hopeful? And what makes you despair about the future of Indian democracy, let's

01:07:00.920 --> 01:07:02.920
[Amit Varma]: say within a 10 year timeframe from now?

01:07:02.920 --> 01:07:08.720
[Guest]: Dr. Ian Lamb So I think what makes me hopeful is that,

01:07:08.720 --> 01:07:14.320
[Guest]: you know, is sort of the legacy of the past in some sense, and that, you know, every 10

01:07:14.320 --> 01:07:20.000
[Guest]: years or so, someone writes a big book, which pronounces, you know, that Indian democracy

01:07:20.000 --> 01:07:25.240
[Guest]: is going to implode. And every 10 years, those people have been proven wrong. I mean, it

01:07:25.240 --> 01:07:30.320
[Guest]: goes back to, you know, Selig Harrison, and the most dangerous decades, which, you know,

01:07:30.320 --> 01:07:34.720
[Guest]: was written, I believe, in the 1950s, or 1960s, saying, you know, this place isn't going to

01:07:34.720 --> 01:07:41.880
[Guest]: last very long. So, you know, Sunil Killnani has this very nice insight in the idea of

01:07:41.880 --> 01:07:47.760
[Guest]: India where he says, it wasn't that there was some grand normative consensus around

01:07:47.760 --> 01:07:54.480
[Guest]: liberal democracy in India, it was basically the only system that could potentially handle

01:07:54.480 --> 01:08:01.760
[Guest]: this constant collision of different interests, and ideas and customs, right, that they were

01:08:01.760 --> 01:08:07.440
[Guest]: constantly clashing, and this was a way to sort of accommodate them. So I think on that

01:08:07.440 --> 01:08:14.680
[Guest]: overall story, I think, sort of still holds, I think one of the emerging issues that we're

01:08:14.680 --> 01:08:22.400
[Guest]: not paying attention to is what is happening in our states across our states, right? There

01:08:22.400 --> 01:08:29.800
[Guest]: is an increasingly entrenched interstate inequality. And it's not just North and South. Well, that's

01:08:29.800 --> 01:08:36.560
[Guest]: one dimension, but it's also kind of an East West story. You've seen the recent stir over

01:08:36.560 --> 01:08:40.760
[Guest]: the Finance Commission and whether or not central transfer should be allocated on the

01:08:40.760 --> 01:08:45.480
[Guest]: basis of population or something else. Obviously, if it was population, you know, the South

01:08:45.480 --> 01:08:51.080
[Guest]: would lose because fertility rates have dropped. There's a question over how you share tax

01:08:51.080 --> 01:08:56.240
[Guest]: revenue, you know, there's a study which shows that on income, you know, the three richest

01:08:56.240 --> 01:09:01.440
[Guest]: states are three times richer than the three poorest states, then there's something that

01:09:01.440 --> 01:09:05.640
[Guest]: I wrote about recently, which is political representation, you know, India's legislatures

01:09:05.640 --> 01:09:11.920
[Guest]: are highly malapportioned, right? We have not updated the statewise breakdown of parliamentary

01:09:11.920 --> 01:09:17.880
[Guest]: seats since 1971. And if you were to do that today, you know, Uttar Pradesh and Bihar would

01:09:17.880 --> 01:09:23.520
[Guest]: get 16 seats and, you know, Karnataka and Tamil Nadu would lose about, you know, 15

01:09:23.520 --> 01:09:29.400
[Guest]: seats. That's a huge shift in political power. And it's only going to get worse. The Constitution

01:09:29.400 --> 01:09:34.360
[Guest]: says you can't change this until 2031 when we do that census, at which time those differences

01:09:34.360 --> 01:09:39.600
[Guest]: are only going to become more pronounced. So I think we're at a stage where we need

01:09:39.600 --> 01:09:45.800
[Guest]: to think of a grand bargain, because Indian federalism was the glue that's kept this project

01:09:45.800 --> 01:09:51.080
[Guest]: together. But I think it's now showing showing its age. So you know, in the 50s, we had the

01:09:51.080 --> 01:09:55.080
[Guest]: state's reorganization commission, right? That was this moment at which we figured out

01:09:55.080 --> 01:10:00.080
[Guest]: how do we create this kind of federal compact. And I think we're in the need for that moment.

01:10:00.080 --> 01:10:04.920
[Guest]: We can't look at each of these issues in isolation. But I fear that's where we're headed.

